{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18532"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18532"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11264"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10701"},{"type":"tags","id":"10708"},{"type":"tags","id":"10711"},{"type":"tags","id":"10713"},{"type":"tags","id":"10736"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"},{"type":"tags","id":"10960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA genetic analysis reveals multiple chromosomal abnormalities in a patient. The karyotype shows numerous fragments from chromosomes 5 and 7 that have been broken and rejoined in a seemingly random pattern. Many segments are missing while others appear in multiple copies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this pattern of chromosomal abnormality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complex chromosomal rearrangement","Robertsonian translocation","Chromosomal inversion","Simple deletion","Reciprocal translocation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplex chromosomal rearrangement\u003C/strong\u003E involves three or more breakpoints affecting two or more chromosomes, resulting in multiple structural changes. These can occur through various mechanisms including chromothripsis (chromosome shattering), chromoanasynthesis (serial duplications), or chromoplexy (chain of rearrangements).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReciprocal translocation\u003C/strong\u003E involves only two chromosomes exchanging segments with two breakpoints\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERobertsonian translocation\u003C/strong\u003E specifically involves fusion of two acrocentric chromosomes at their centromeres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChromosomal inversion\u003C/strong\u003E involves a single chromosome segment that is flipped and reinserted\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple deletion\u003C/strong\u003E involves loss of a single chromosomal segment with only one breakpoint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplex rearrangements are found in various clinical contexts including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConstitutional disorders causing developmental delay and congenital anomalies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFertility problems due to abnormal meiotic segregation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcquired changes in cancer cells, particularly in aggressive tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complex chromosomal rearrangements involve three or more breakpoints across two or more chromosomes.","Complex rearrangements can result in multiple deletion, duplication, and translocation events simultaneously.","Complex chromosomal rearrangements are associated with developmental disorders, infertility, and some cancers."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Brooker RJ. Genetics: Analysis and Principles. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Education; 2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18532"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T21:28:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T21:29:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11264"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79523"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpret